    <div class='deck-container'>
      <!-- Content Begins Below -->
      <div class='slide' id='0'><h1>Poi Recorder Project</h1>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='1'><h2>Description</h2>
      
      <p>This project will capture the movements of dancers and play the back.</p>

      
      <p>The motivation is that the movements of these performers are often subconscious and difficult to analyze.</p>
      
      <p>One particular type of dance I would like to capture is the art of tech poi.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='2'><h2>Libraries</h2>
      
      <p>OpenNI - Kinect interface</p>
      
      <p>NITE - Skeleton tracking library</p>
      
      <p>Uses C++ for all programming components.</p>

      
      <p>Is platform independent.</p>
      
      <p>Code is on Github.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='3'><h2>How does it work</h2>
      
      <p>Kinect tracks skeleton.</p>
      
      <p>The joint positions are recorded.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='4'><h2>Two Modes</h2>

      
      <ul>
      <li><p>Recorder</p></li>
      <li><p>Player</p></li>
      </ul>
      
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='5'><h2>Recorder</h2>
      
      <p>The recorder will wait until a skeleton is tracked.</p>
      
      <p>You go into the "cactus" pose to start tracking.</p>

      
      <p>The output goes into the recording.poi file.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='6'><h2>Datafile</h2>
      
      <p>The file is simply a collection of timings and joint positions.</p>
      
      <p>The resolution of the image is the first line.</p>
      
      <p>This is followed by tuples {x, y, z} for 15 joints.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='7'><h2>Player</h2>

      
      <p>This datafile can be read by the same program when it is given as an argument.</p>
      
      <p>The player accepts another argument for the rate to play the recording.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='8'><h2>Player Screenshot</h2>
      
      <p><img alt="Player Screen" src="screen.png" style="height: 450px" /></p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='9'><h2>Components</h2>
      
      <p>Kinect - Class that drives the kinect device and handles callbacks.</p>

      
      <p>Player - Plays a recording.</p>
      
      <p>Canvas - Draws to the screen.</p>
      
      <p>Presenter - Handles what to draw using the Canvas.</p>
      
      <p>Window - Abstracts platform window APIs.</p>
      
      <p>InputHandler - Handles keyboard input.</p>
      
      <p>PointDrawer - Draws backgrounds.</p>

      
      <p>UserDrawer - Draws skeleton.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='10'><h2>Problems</h2>
      
      <p>Cannot track joints that go behind a person.</p>
      
      <p>Poi head is actually difficult to track (with my limited expertise).</p>
      
      <p>Accuracy is pretty bad.</p>
      
      </div><div class='slide' id='11'><h2>Future Work</h2>

      
      <p>Attempt to teach the program how to track poi.</p>
      
      <p>Use two Kinects to see all angles.</p>
      
      <p>Advanced playback and choreography tools.</p>
      </div>
      <!-- Content Ended -->
